  <content>
    <title>Rust Backend (Axum)</title>

    <summary>Opinionated layout and patterns for Rust HTTP services using Axum: one AppError enum per service with IntoResponse mapping to RFC 7807, layered modules (routes/, handlers/, services/, models/, db/), AppState shared via Arc, CPU-bound work on spawn_blocking, and a vertical-slice delivery model (models → db → services → handlers → routes + tests in one PR).</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Rust's type system eliminates entire categories of bugs, but the Axum API surface changed significantly between 0.6 and 0.7 and LLMs blend the two. A single canonical shape for AppState, AppError, handler signatures, and test scaffolding prevents silent contract breaks and keeps agent-generated PRs coherent across services.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Greenfield Rust HTTP service needing full project layout + handlers + services + DB + tests.</item>
        <item>Migrating a Python/Node service to Rust for tail-latency or memory reasons.</item>
        <item>Standardizing several Rust services on one shape (same AppError, handler/service/db split, test scaffolding).</item>
        <item>Onboarding new contributors who need a working CRUD slice without learning Tokio/Axum trivia first.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Library crates (no HTTP) — only the project-structure portion applies.</item>
        <item>gRPC-only services — use tonic; handler shape differs.</item>
        <item>Lambda/Cloud-Functions — lambda_runtime plus a minimal handler is leaner.</item>
        <item>Embedded/no_std — use embassy instead.</item>
        <item>Cross-runtime libraries — drop Tokio specifics.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="directory-layout">
      <p>Directory structure, module wiring, Axum router setup, and AppState shape for Rust HTTP services.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Organise source into routes/, handlers/, services/, models/, db/, middleware/, error.rs, config.rs. Each layer depends only on the layer below it.</statement>
        <rationale>Vertical consistency across services lets any engineer find files without reading a README. The compiler enforces the dependency direction.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Standard Rust backend layout">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[src/
├── main.rs          # tokio::main, server startup
├── lib.rs           # re-exports AppState, AppError
├── config.rs        # Config::from_env()
├── error.rs         # AppError enum + IntoResponse
├── routes/
│   ├── mod.rs       # api_routes() → Router<AppState>
│   └── users.rs
├── handlers/
│   ├── mod.rs
│   └── users.rs
├── services/
│   ├── mod.rs
│   └── users.rs
├── models/
│   ├── mod.rs
│   └── user.rs
├── db/
│   ├── mod.rs
│   └── users.rs
└── middleware/
    ├── mod.rs
    └── auth.rs
migrations/
tests/]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="appstate">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Wrap all heavy fields in Arc. Pass State(state): State&lt;AppState&gt; to handlers — never individual sub-fields. Keep AppState Clone-cheap.</statement>
        <rationale>Axum clones AppState per request. Wrapping Database, Config, etc. in Arc makes the clone O(1) and avoids accidental copies of connection pools.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="handler-pattern">
      <p>Axum handler pattern with typed extractors, service layer with tokio::try_join! for parallel queries, and spawn_blocking for CPU-bound work.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Handlers return Result&lt;impl IntoResponse, AppError&gt;. Extract State, Path, Query, Json as typed parameters. Validate with the validator crate before calling the service.</statement>
        <rationale>Axum calls IntoResponse on the Ok and Err variants. A typed AppError that implements IntoResponse keeps HTTP mapping out of service code.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Type-safe handler with validation">
        <code lang="rust"><![CDATA[pub async fn create(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    Json(payload): Json<CreateUserRequest>,
) -> Result<(StatusCode, Json<UserResponse>), AppError> {
    payload.validate()?;
    let service = UserService::new(&state.db);
    let user = service.create(&payload.name, &payload.email, &payload.password).await?;
    Ok((StatusCode::CREATED, Json(user.into())))
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="parallel-queries">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use tokio::try_join! to run independent DB queries concurrently rather than awaiting them sequentially.</statement>
        <rationale>Sequential awaits for count + fetch add latency proportional to one RTT. try_join! runs both in parallel and fails fast on the first error.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Parallel queries with try_join!">
        <code lang="rust"><![CDATA[pub async fn list(&self, page: u32, per_page: u32) -> Result<(Vec<User>, i64), AppError> {
    let offset = ((page - 1) * per_page) as i64;
    let (users, total) = tokio::try_join!(
        self.db.fetch_users(per_page as i64, offset),
        self.db.count_users()
    )?;
    Ok((users, total))
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="spawn-blocking">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run CPU-intensive work (Argon2, bcrypt, large serialisation) via tokio::task::spawn_blocking. Never block the async executor with synchronous CPU loops.</statement>
        <rationale>Async runtimes use a small thread pool. A blocking call on an async thread starves other tasks waiting for their poll.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="unit-testing">
      <p>Unit tests with mockall trait abstractions and integration tests using tower::ServiceExt::oneshot.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define a DatabaseTrait (or Repository trait) abstraction and mock it with mockall::mock!. Never mock a concrete struct whose methods use sqlx::query! macros — those embed file paths at compile time.</statement>
        <rationale>sqlx::query! macros require DATABASE_URL at compile time. Mocking the concrete Database struct breaks when these macros are present. A trait abstraction separates the DB interface from the implementation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Unit test with mockall">
        <code lang="rust"><![CDATA[#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;
    use mockall::predicate::*;
    use mockall::mock;

    mock! {
        Database {}
        impl Database {
            async fn fetch_user_by_id(&self, id: i32) -> Result<Option<User>, sqlx::Error>;
        }
    }

    #[tokio::test]
    async fn test_get_by_id_returns_user() {
        let mut mock_db = MockDatabase::new();
        mock_db
            .expect_fetch_user_by_id()
            .with(eq(1))
            .times(1)
            .returning(|_| Ok(Some(create_test_user())));
        let service = UserService::new(&mock_db);
        let result = service.get_by_id(1).await;
        assert!(result.is_ok());
    }

    #[tokio::test]
    async fn test_get_by_id_not_found() {
        let mut mock_db = MockDatabase::new();
        mock_db
            .expect_fetch_user_by_id()
            .with(eq(999))
            .returning(|_| Ok(None));
        let service = UserService::new(&mock_db);
        let result = service.get_by_id(999).await;
        assert!(matches!(result, Err(AppError::NotFound(_))));
    }
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="intoresponse-coverage">
      <p>Critical failure modes in LLM-generated Axum code and the corresponding rules to prevent them.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every variant of AppError must appear in the IntoResponse match arm. Adding a new variant without updating IntoResponse compiles but panics at runtime via the unreachable default.</statement>
        <rationale>Rust does not force exhaustive matching when the fallback arm is present. A missing variant silently returns 500 with an empty body instead of the intended status code.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding a new AppError variant and relying on a wildcard arm in IntoResponse.</description>
        <reason>Wildcard arms hide the contract break. Require explicit per-variant match at code review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="validator-error-mapping">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Map validator::ValidationErrors to per-field error arrays in the response. Never return the raw ValidationErrors debug string — it leaks field names in an uncontrolled format.</statement>
        <rationale>The default Display for ValidationErrors is not RFC 7807 compatible. Clients receive an opaque string instead of a structured errors array.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="sqlx-pool-cloning">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Clone an sqlx::Pool to share across tasks — cloning is O(1) (Arc internally). Never call Pool::connect per request to "fix" Send issues.</statement>
        <rationale>Pool::connect opens a new TCP connection. Calling it per request exhausts file descriptors under load. Pool clone shares the existing connection pool cheaply.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="middleware-order">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Layer middleware in this order, outer to inner: TraceLayer, request-id, CORS, auth, rate-limit, app router. Adding layers in wrong order silently misses authentication.</statement>
        <rationale>Axum applies middleware from outermost to innermost. Auth middleware added after the route handler is never reached.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="sqlx-prepare">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run sqlx prepare and commit the .sqlx/ directory so CI builds without requiring DATABASE_URL at compile time.</statement>
        <rationale>sqlx::query! macros verify SQL against a live DB at compile time. Without cached query data, offline builds and CI without a DB fail.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>The agent should drive a vertical slice: pick the entity, generate models/&lt;x&gt;.rs, db/&lt;x&gt;.rs, services/&lt;x&gt;.rs, handlers/&lt;x&gt;.rs, routes/&lt;x&gt;.rs, and integration tests in one PR. Always start by reading Cargo.toml, error.rs, and AppState to keep types consistent. After implementation, run cargo fmt, cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings, cargo nextest run, and a smoke-test curl against the new endpoint via cargo run in a sandbox. For a brand-new repo, the agent should bootstrap the layout before generating the first slice. Schema/DB changes ride along but should land as a separate commit when reasonable.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every variant of AppError must have an IntoResponse arm. Use exhaustive matching on enum variants, not wildcard defaults.</statement>
        <rationale>Missing IntoResponse arms compile (via default catch-all) but panic at runtime with 500 + empty body instead of the intended status.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Best practices for Rust HTTP services:</p>
      <list>
        <item>One AppError enum per service; never use anyhow::Error at API boundaries.</item>
        <item>#[tokio::main] only in main.rs; library code stays runtime-agnostic where possible.</item>
        <item>Keep AppState cheap to clone (wrap heavy fields in Arc); Axum clones it per request.</item>
        <item>Pass &amp;AppState extractors, not individual sub-fields, to avoid signature churn.</item>
        <item>Use tracing::instrument on every handler and service method with skip(state, password).</item>
        <item>Run integration tests with a real PG via testcontainers or a transactional rollback wrapper.</item>
        <item>sqlx prepare and check in .sqlx/ so CI builds without DATABASE_URL.</item>
        <item>Pin minor versions of Axum/sqlx/tokio in Cargo.toml; commit Cargo.lock for binaries.</item>
        <item>Layer middleware: TraceLayer, request-id, CORS, auth, rate-limit, app router (outer to inner).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="testing-gotchas">
      <p>Common testing issues in Rust HTTP services:</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Axum 0.6 vs 0.7 handler signature mismatches in LLM-generated code.</description>
        <reason>API changed significantly between versions. Read Cargo.toml first to pin the version.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents copy lifetime annotations (UserService&lt;'a&gt;) blindly, failing on tokio::spawn.</description>
        <reason>Tokio requires 'static bounds. Prefer Arc&lt;Database&gt; ownership over borrowed references.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>mockall cannot mock structs with sqlx::query! macros due to file-path embeddings.</description>
        <reason>Use trait abstractions that the agent must derive instead of raw struct mocking.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs forget to add IntoResponse for new AppError variants.</description>
        <reason>Build passes (default impl) but runtime panics. Require exhaustive match audit.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Password hashing inlined in async fns instead of spawn_blocking.</description>
        <reason>Blocks the async executor. Argon2/bcrypt must run off-thread via spawn_blocking.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Validator integration leaks entire ValidationErrors debug string in responses.</description>
        <reason>Expose individual field errors in structured format, not raw error debug output.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Essential CLI tools for Rust backend development:</p>
      <list>
        <item>cargo: Build/test/run — https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/</item>
        <item>cargo nextest: Faster, parallel test runner — https://nexte.st</item>
        <item>cargo watch: Recompile on change — cargo install cargo-watch</item>
        <item>cargo clippy: Lint — rustup component</item>
        <item>cargo fmt: Format — rustup component</item>
        <item>cargo audit: RustSec advisories — https://github.com/rustsec/rustsec</item>
        <item>sqlx-cli: Migrations + query check — https://github.com/launchbadge/sqlx</item>
        <item>cargo expand: See macro expansions — https://github.com/dtolnay/cargo-expand</item>
        <item>tokio-console: Live runtime view — https://github.com/tokio-rs/console</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/app-error.rs" purpose="AppError enum with IntoResponse mapping to RFC 7807 ProblemDetail."/>
    </templates>

